    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-10-23T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-10-23T06:00:00-05:00" n="713"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d713">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">762.9411/129: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Matthews</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>(<hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>) <hi rend="smallcaps">Vichy</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-10-23T13:00:00+02:00"
                            >October 23, 1940—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 8:13 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>804. Chauvel<note n="89" xml:id="d713fn89">Jean Chauvel, head of Far Eastern
                        section, French Foreign Office.</note> showed me this morning a telegram
                    received from Arsene-Henry<note n="90" xml:id="d713fn90">Charles Arsène-Henry,
                        French Ambassador in Japan.</note> at Tokyo under date of October 22. That
                    telegram reported that while there seemed to be no secret clause to the recent
                    tripartite pact he had ascertained that there was a <hi rend="italic"
                        >procès-verbal</hi> specifically providing that Japan would not be required
                    automatically to make war on the United States if we become involved in
                    hostilities against Germany as a result of action taken by the latter. This <hi
                        rend="italic">procès-verbal</hi>, said Henry, specifically provided that
                    Japan should have the right to examine the circumstances before taking any
                    position.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Matthews</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
